Q20: I was flagged for 10 years after Canadian border patrol detained me crossing the border in a car in 2009. I was assumed to be Native American and a reporter. I was routinely stopped and asked additional questions about my background and travel plans. Sometimes they focused on my Mexican heritage, other times they focused on their assumption I was Native American. I was frequently asked questions that appeared to me were based on me being a young woman traveling alone who might be smuggling items or looking for under the table work. Whenever I came back to the US, I had an X on my face at ports of entry and had to go through additional revision. Even my travel partners were discouraged from staying with me and I felt Border Patrol attempted to isolate me from companions when I was not alone.

Q20: An international flight moved two hours earlier the day before takeoff and I did not notice. When I arrived at the gate, I actually arrived with the pilot who was on the transport train with me. It was just the two of us. When we got to the gate, he got on the plane and I wasn't allowed on the plane because the process to verify my information would "take too long." The flight attendant didn't try or give an opportunity when all of my information was in my hands and ready to go. She displayed assertiveness and refused to let me finish my sentences without interrupting. The pilot stayed out of it, got on the plane, and took off. I went through several international customs during my trip through various countries, including another flight to the same destination in the same airport on the same day for 4x the price and the approval process for the flight took less than five minutes. She could have helped me but it felt racially motivated based on me being late for flight I originally would've been early for. It took a full month to get my money back after building a case based on her behavior, and the behavior of several airline representatives and the poor customer service proved to be undeniable. Avianca was the airline.

Q20: After the terrorist attacks on 9-11-2001, I was put on the do not fly list because of my name.  After experiencing multiple delays getting a boarding pass,  security checks, immigration,  and customs,  I asked a customs officer what I can do to avoid such delays in the future and clear my name.  He suggested that I apply for Global Entry,  which I promptly did.  Global Entry qualification entails a background check by Federal authorities and an in person interview.   After I was approved for Global Entry,  I was entitled to expedited security checks at the airport abd also a special expedited immigration and customs check upon entry to the US.  I have utilized this service for over 8 years and have not experienced any random checks or delays while traveling.  I recommend this service to anyone who complains about delays or discrimination at the airports.
